('Kerley B line are seen at', 'Ans. is \'d\' i.e., Pleural surface Kerley\'s line Kerley\'s line is a linear opacity which, depending on its locaton, extent and orientation, may be be fuher classified as :? Kerley\'s A lines o These are thin, non-branching lines radiating from hilum. These lines are 2-6 cm in length. These lines are found in the mid and upper zones of the lung fields pleural. These lines are due to the thick interlobar septa. Kerley\'s B lines (septal lines) These are transverse (Horizontal) lines at the lung base pleural. These are 1-2 cm in length and are perpendicular to pleura. Kerley\'s B line is due to the thickening of interlobar septa due to edema caused by pulmonary venous hypeension (congestion), as occurs in left ventricular failure or mitral stenosis', 4, 'Apex', 'Cardiophrenic angle', 'Lung fissure', 'Pleural surface', 'Medicine', '', '81697ce5-1551-43f9-a2c6-b41cf41fb01b', 65, 53, '18.46', 49),
